{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508949"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:11:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:11:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11364"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11364"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.17,0.23,0.44,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110482"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4009"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11364"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92746"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3504"},{"type":"tags","id":"3514"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11426"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43217"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110482"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman with type I diabetes mellitus (T1DM) presents seeking counselling on the management of her diabetes, if and when she chooses to become pregnant. Her case notes record poor adherence issues with her insulin treatment since she turned 18. She is given information and advice about pregnancy and diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most accurate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["She should be commenced on aspirin 150 mg daily throughout the pregnancy","She should be advised to commence folic acid 400 \u03bcg daily","She should aim for a HbA1c between 7-8% during pregnancy","The foetus might be at risk of congenital anomalies","Retinal screening should be performed during every trimester"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPre-existing diabetes is linked to a nine-fold rise in \u003Cstrong\u003Econgenital anomalies\u003C/strong\u003E, primarily affecting the cardiovascular, central nervous, and skeletal systems. Caudal regression syndrome, a rare anomaly exclusively linked to diabetes, involves femoral shortening and sacral agenesis. Maintaining HbA1c within the target range before and during early pregnancy minimises the risk of diabetes-related congenital anomalies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ET1DM (15\u201320% incidence) and T2DM (10\u201315% incidence) both significantly increase the risk of pre-eclampsia. Therefore, all patients with pre-existing diabetes should take aspirin 100\u2013150 mg daily with the evening meal (unless contraindicated) from 12 weeks gestation. However, this medication should be discontinued at 36 weeks gestation to minimise the risk of intrapartum and postpartum haemorrhage and therefore \u003Cstrong\u003Easpirin is not to be recommended throughout the entirety\u003C/strong\u003E of a woman\u0027s pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFolate requirements rise during pregnancy, and supplementing 400 \u03bcg (0.4 mg) folic acid/day is beneficial for reducing neural tube defects (NTDs) in the general pregnant population. However, women with diabetes face an elevated NTD risk. They should start a higher \u003Cstrong\u003Efolic acid \u003C/strong\u003Edosage of 2.5\u20135 mg daily three months before conception and continue until 12 weeks gestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe should aim for a HbA1c between 7-8% during pregnancy \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be the correct advice to give this patient. According to guidelines, she should aim for a HbA1c of less than 7%, and ideally less than 6.5%. HbA1c \u0026gt;8% is associated with an increased incidence of birth defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWomen with pre-existing diabetes should be informed about the risks of developing new-onset and/or progression of diabetic retinopathy (DR) during pregnancy. \u003Cstrong\u003ERetinal screening \u003C/strong\u003Eshould occur in the first trimester (unless done within 3 months pre-conception), and a repeat screen in the third trimester is advisable if no DR is detected initially. Renal screening, including serum creatinine, and spot urine ACR or protein: creatinine ratio (PCR), should be conducted in each trimester.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tight glycaemic control is crucial during pregnancy in patients with diabetes.","The medical care for pregnant women with diabetes is complex and requires input from several medical specialties and health professionals."],"references":["Rudland VL, Price SA, Hughes R, Barrett HL, Lagstrom J, Porter C, Britten FL, Glastras S, Fulcher I, Wein P, Simmons D. ADIPS 2020 guideline for pre\u2010existing diabetes and pregnancy. Australian and New Zealand Journal of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. 2020 Dec;60(6):E18-52.  https://obgyn.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/ajo.13265#","Gabbay-Benziv R, Reece EA, Wang F, Yang P. Birth defects in pregestational diabetes: Defect range, glycemic threshold and pathogenesis. World journal of diabetes. 2015 Apr 4;6(3):481. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4398903/","Vargas R, Repke J, Ural S. Type 1 diabetes mellitus and pregnancy. Rev Obstet Gynecol. 2010 Summer;3(3):92-100. Rev Obstet Gynecol [Internet]. 2010 [cited 8 August 2022];3(3):92-100. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3046748/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92746"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11364"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92746"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-31T12:01:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-31T12:01:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4009"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110482"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.em